WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.067 --> 00:00:04.000
RONALD SMITH: Well we're
going to talk about El

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:05.967
Nino today.

00:00:05.967 --> 00:00:09.733
I've got a PowerPoint
presentation, but before I get

00:00:09.733 --> 00:00:11.633
into that, I wanted to give
a bunch of definitions.

00:00:11.633 --> 00:00:21.300
So El Nino is a naturally
occurring oscillation in the

00:00:21.300 --> 00:00:27.333
Pacific Ocean between two
rather distinct states.

00:00:31.133 --> 00:00:37.867
El Nino was defined about 30
or 40 years ago as a state

00:00:37.867 --> 00:00:39.433
that the ocean went
into occasionally.

00:00:42.533 --> 00:00:45.333
Originally it was defined as a
condition of having warmer

00:00:45.333 --> 00:00:50.900
than usual waters in the Eastern
Tropical Pacific, and

00:00:50.900 --> 00:00:54.433
low biological productivity.

00:00:54.433 --> 00:00:57.500
Those two things were the
original definition.

00:00:57.500 --> 00:01:00.200
As we began to study it, we
realized that there are many

00:01:00.200 --> 00:01:04.333
other things going on involving
trade wind strength,

00:01:04.333 --> 00:01:07.500
Walker circulation,
precipitation patterns.

00:01:07.500 --> 00:01:13.000
So now it is-- definition has
broadened to include a number

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:19.133
of related symptoms, and I'll
be discussing those in the

00:01:19.133 --> 00:01:20.367
PowerPoint presentation.

00:01:20.367 --> 00:01:21.900
Let me go through these
two diagrams to

00:01:21.900 --> 00:01:23.133
kind of get it started.

00:01:26.067 --> 00:01:29.067
Now, one thing that's most
curious about this is that

00:01:29.067 --> 00:01:34.533
these two states can exist
without any external forcing.

00:01:34.533 --> 00:01:36.800
It's like one day you wake up
in the morning and you feel

00:01:36.800 --> 00:01:38.633
great, another morning you wake
up in the morning you

00:01:38.633 --> 00:01:42.300
feel crummy, and there's nothing
external necessarily

00:01:42.300 --> 00:01:43.133
that's driving this.

00:01:43.133 --> 00:01:46.400
It's just kind of
the way it is.

00:01:46.400 --> 00:01:48.533
Well El Nino's not exactly
like that.

00:01:48.533 --> 00:01:50.433
There's a lot of physics
involved in it.

00:01:50.433 --> 00:01:53.733
But it doesn't seem to be driven
by anything external.

00:01:53.733 --> 00:01:58.067
It's not the Sun, it's not the
tilt of the Earth, it's not

00:01:58.067 --> 00:02:02.267
some kind of change occurring
by human-induced changes.

00:02:02.267 --> 00:02:07.100
It just seems to have periods of
several months when it does

00:02:07.100 --> 00:02:09.567
one thing and periods of several
months when it does

00:02:09.567 --> 00:02:11.300
something else.

00:02:11.300 --> 00:02:13.833
And this will kind of get you
started on the discussion.

00:02:13.833 --> 00:02:17.900
So I've got two identical
cross-sections here.

00:02:17.900 --> 00:02:24.367
They run West to East through
the Equatorial Pacific Ocean.

00:02:24.367 --> 00:02:29.467
So there's Asia on this side,
the Andes in South

00:02:29.467 --> 00:02:31.233
America on this side.

00:02:31.233 --> 00:02:34.133
The International Date Line
would be somewhere in the

00:02:34.133 --> 00:02:38.633
middle that'd be 180 degrees
West or East longitude.

00:02:41.233 --> 00:02:45.267
And most of the time you've
got a situation that looks

00:02:45.267 --> 00:02:46.267
something like this.

00:02:46.267 --> 00:02:53.700
You've got very warm water in
the Western Pacific, warm air

00:02:53.700 --> 00:02:57.467
as well, and because of that
you've got a lot of convective

00:02:57.467 --> 00:02:59.400
precipitation.

00:02:59.400 --> 00:03:03.100
Sometimes this part of the ocean
is called the warm pool.

00:03:03.100 --> 00:03:06.800
If you say a warm pool to an
oceanographer or to an

00:03:06.800 --> 00:03:10.233
atmospheric scientist, they know
that you're referring, or

00:03:10.233 --> 00:03:13.167
they suspect you're referring to
the Western Pacific because

00:03:13.167 --> 00:03:17.167
there we get the warmest ocean
temperatures anywhere on the

00:03:17.167 --> 00:03:20.667
globe, at least during
this phase of the El

00:03:20.667 --> 00:03:21.933
Nino, La Nina cycle.

00:03:21.933 --> 00:03:26.433
So this is a warm pool in the
Western Equatorial and

00:03:26.433 --> 00:03:28.267
Tropical Pacific.

00:03:28.267 --> 00:03:32.567
Lower atmospheric pressure
because the air is warmer, and

00:03:32.567 --> 00:03:35.200
because the air is warm it's
less dense, so the pressure

00:03:35.200 --> 00:03:40.167
underneath, warmer air is
usually lower pressure.

00:03:40.167 --> 00:03:43.500
During those periods of time you
have strong Easterly trade

00:03:43.500 --> 00:03:48.633
winds, so I've drawn
them this way.

00:03:48.633 --> 00:03:53.500
The trade winds return a loft
in what's called the Walker

00:03:53.500 --> 00:03:55.067
circulation.

00:03:55.067 --> 00:03:59.533
So remember, the Hadley cell you
would see if I sliced it

00:03:59.533 --> 00:04:02.333
this way, across the Equator,
here I'm slicing

00:04:02.333 --> 00:04:03.733
it along the Equator.

00:04:03.733 --> 00:04:06.400
So we don't see the Hadley
circulation, but we do see

00:04:06.400 --> 00:04:09.767
this Walker circulation.

00:04:09.767 --> 00:04:13.400
It returns the low level
Easterlies in upper level

00:04:13.400 --> 00:04:14.533
Westerlies.

00:04:14.533 --> 00:04:19.400
In the Eastern Tropical Pacific
you have generally

00:04:19.400 --> 00:04:23.233
higher air pressure.

00:04:23.233 --> 00:04:28.667
Cooler ocean waters, and the
cooler waters makes it, at the

00:04:28.667 --> 00:04:34.233
surface, makes it easier for
nutrient rich water from below

00:04:34.233 --> 00:04:37.933
to mix up to the surface, in
part due to coastal upwelling

00:04:37.933 --> 00:04:41.133
that we spoke about last time.

00:04:41.133 --> 00:04:43.233
And as a result of that, you
have generally a high

00:04:43.233 --> 00:04:50.167
biological productivity during
this phase of the cycle.

00:04:50.167 --> 00:04:55.233
So let's say then we go into
an El Nino situation.

00:04:55.233 --> 00:04:59.100
Now the word El Nino comes from
the fact that when this

00:04:59.100 --> 00:05:06.533
switchover occurs, it usually
occurs in November, December

00:05:06.533 --> 00:05:11.600
or January, not too far from
the Christmas season.

00:05:11.600 --> 00:05:14.167
The countries along the West
Coast of South America are

00:05:14.167 --> 00:05:19.333
generally Catholic in their
religion, and the Christ child

00:05:19.333 --> 00:05:20.533
is worshipped.

00:05:20.533 --> 00:05:23.767
And the fact that this
switchover, when it occurs,

00:05:23.767 --> 00:05:27.467
usually occurred within a few
weeks of Christmastime meant

00:05:27.467 --> 00:05:29.400
that it was given the
name El Nino, the

00:05:29.400 --> 00:05:31.100
child, the Christ child.

00:05:31.100 --> 00:05:33.633
That's where the term
comes from.

00:05:33.633 --> 00:05:35.600
So it has kind of everything
reversed.

00:05:35.600 --> 00:05:40.267
You've got weaker trade winds,
cooler than usual ocean

00:05:40.267 --> 00:05:44.033
temperatures and air
temperatures, higher air

00:05:44.033 --> 00:05:48.433
pressures, the Walker
circulation is weakened, I

00:05:48.433 --> 00:05:52.000
haven't drawn it here lower
pressure than usual in the

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:54.900
East side of the Pacific.

00:05:54.900 --> 00:05:59.767
Along with precipitation
occurring along the coast of

00:05:59.767 --> 00:06:02.267
South American near
the Equator.

00:06:02.267 --> 00:06:05.533
With the warm water here
you have strongly

00:06:05.533 --> 00:06:09.100
stabilized the ocean.

00:06:09.100 --> 00:06:11.633
Warm water floating
above cold water.

00:06:11.633 --> 00:06:14.500
The nutrients are still down
there below, but they can't

00:06:14.500 --> 00:06:20.533
mix to the surface, so you get
a low biological productivity

00:06:20.533 --> 00:06:25.500
in that part of the cycle.

00:06:25.500 --> 00:06:26.300
Any questions on that?

00:06:26.300 --> 00:06:26.733
Yes.

00:06:26.733 --> 00:06:29.067
STUDENT: Why does the Walker
Circulation weaken?

00:06:29.067 --> 00:06:31.333
PROFESSOR: Well because it's part of this--

00:06:31.333 --> 00:06:36.133
the air that goes Westward in
the trade wind has to move

00:06:36.133 --> 00:06:37.067
back Eastward.

00:06:37.067 --> 00:06:41.067
So that whole circulation is
called the Walker circ--

00:06:41.067 --> 00:06:45.600
it's just closing the
cycle on the strong

00:06:45.600 --> 00:06:47.267
Easterly trade winds.

00:06:47.267 --> 00:06:51.033
But remember, when air in the
Walker circulation reaches

00:06:51.033 --> 00:06:56.300
this point and then tries to
descend to match up with this,

00:06:56.300 --> 00:06:59.633
that descending air is going to
prevent clouds from forming

00:06:59.633 --> 00:07:02.900
here, and that's consistent
with what I've drawn.

00:07:02.900 --> 00:07:06.833
And here, when this air has to
ascend to then form the rest

00:07:06.833 --> 00:07:09.667
of the Walker circulation, the
ascent occurs in these

00:07:09.667 --> 00:07:10.767
convective clouds.

00:07:10.767 --> 00:07:12.567
So that's consistent as well.

00:07:12.567 --> 00:07:14.933
Then when I've weakened the
Walker circulation, that's

00:07:14.933 --> 00:07:16.400
consistent with the
way I've drawn the

00:07:16.400 --> 00:07:18.233
clouds there as well.

00:07:18.233 --> 00:07:20.633
So there are physical laws
connecting all of

00:07:20.633 --> 00:07:22.100
these things together.

00:07:22.100 --> 00:07:25.233
But on this diagram, and in
fact, in most of what I'll be

00:07:25.233 --> 00:07:28.067
saying today, there's going to
be very little explanation

00:07:28.067 --> 00:07:32.200
about why the system would
switch back and forth.

00:07:32.200 --> 00:07:36.100
So I'm mostly going to be
talking about what we observe

00:07:36.100 --> 00:07:40.633
the atmosphere ocean to do in
this part of the world, how

00:07:40.633 --> 00:07:45.000
the various symptoms tie
together physically.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:47.967
But the scientific community
does not have a clear

00:07:47.967 --> 00:07:51.067
understanding of what would
make this system suddenly

00:07:51.067 --> 00:07:54.467
switch from one phase
to the other.

00:07:54.467 --> 00:07:57.400
So I'm not going to spend a lot
of time dealing with that.

00:07:57.400 --> 00:08:01.133
It's kind of one of the
remaining unknowns.

00:08:01.133 --> 00:08:02.867
It's not that there hasn't
been work on it, it's not

00:08:02.867 --> 00:08:06.400
there hasn't been theories
proposed, but I would say it's

00:08:06.400 --> 00:08:09.733
not a solved problem in terms
of what causes the system to

00:08:09.733 --> 00:08:11.500
cycle back and forth
like this.

00:08:14.067 --> 00:08:21.400
So I'll get in now to the way
some of these things look.

00:08:30.067 --> 00:08:31.333
And stop me if you
have questions.

00:08:38.633 --> 00:08:42.633
So it's a natural oscillation
in the air-sea state of the

00:08:42.633 --> 00:08:46.167
Tropical Pacific Ocean.

00:08:46.167 --> 00:08:49.167
I'm going to start out with
a lot of attention

00:08:49.167 --> 00:08:51.167
paid to this region.

00:08:51.167 --> 00:08:55.067
We described it last time as a
region of coastal upwelling.

00:08:55.067 --> 00:08:58.767
And that, indeed, is where the
studies of El Nino began.

00:08:58.767 --> 00:09:01.133
That's where it was first
identified, and that's where a

00:09:01.133 --> 00:09:03.700
number of the early definitions
come from is the

00:09:03.700 --> 00:09:07.700
variability along the Peruvian
Coast there.

00:09:11.967 --> 00:09:14.567
And to remind you, a typical
well, this is not necessarily

00:09:14.567 --> 00:09:19.433
typical, this is a temperature
anomaly from a year ago, just

00:09:19.433 --> 00:09:23.233
about a year ago today these
are what the sea surface

00:09:23.233 --> 00:09:27.267
temperature anomalies
look like.

00:09:27.267 --> 00:09:30.867
The blue means cooler, so you've
got a cooler water than

00:09:30.867 --> 00:09:34.933
usual in the Eastern Tropical
Pacific a year ago.

00:09:34.933 --> 00:09:37.600
And which side of the cycle?

00:09:37.600 --> 00:09:40.700
Is that El Nino or La Nina?

00:09:40.700 --> 00:09:41.600
STUDENT: La Nina.

00:09:41.600 --> 00:09:42.567
PROFESSOR: La Nina, right.

00:09:42.567 --> 00:09:49.300
So a year ago, there was a La
Nina existing, because you can

00:09:49.300 --> 00:09:52.400
identify that immediately
because of the colder than

00:09:52.400 --> 00:09:55.933
usual conditions in the sea
surface temperature in the

00:09:55.933 --> 00:09:58.400
Eastern Tropical Pacific.

00:09:58.400 --> 00:10:01.200
So a year ago there was La Nina,
and near the end of the

00:10:01.200 --> 00:10:03.700
presentation I'll bring that
up to date, we'll see what

00:10:03.700 --> 00:10:08.333
state the Tropical Pacific
has today.

00:10:08.333 --> 00:10:11.667
So here's what you need to
know for terminology.

00:10:11.667 --> 00:10:14.333
I wasn't able to get the umlauts
over the n's there.

00:10:14.333 --> 00:10:18.867
But El Nino and La Nina, which
are the phases of this

00:10:18.867 --> 00:10:23.267
oscillation, the Southern
Oscillation Index is defined

00:10:23.267 --> 00:10:27.967
as the pressure difference
between Darwin in Australia,

00:10:27.967 --> 00:10:35.333
and Tahiti in the Eastern
Central Pacific Ocean, and

00:10:35.333 --> 00:10:39.200
that is a measure of this
pressure oscillation that I

00:10:39.200 --> 00:10:39.933
told you about.

00:10:39.933 --> 00:10:43.200
So on occasion you'll see
plots of the Southern

00:10:43.200 --> 00:10:47.267
Oscillation Index, and
that's the pressure

00:10:47.267 --> 00:10:50.367
symptom of this cycle.

00:10:50.367 --> 00:10:52.100
The Walker circulation
I've defined.

00:10:52.100 --> 00:10:56.100
It's a circulation that occurs
more or less in the plane of

00:10:56.100 --> 00:11:00.900
the Equator, taking some of
the trade wind flow and

00:11:00.900 --> 00:11:04.600
returning it back to the
East aloft in the upper

00:11:04.600 --> 00:11:06.667
troposphere.

00:11:06.667 --> 00:11:10.967
In a few minutes I'll show you
the TOA array, which we now

00:11:10.967 --> 00:11:14.233
use to monitor El Nino.

00:11:14.233 --> 00:11:17.233
It's quite a remarkable set
of instrumentation.

00:11:17.233 --> 00:11:20.133
Sea surface temperature we
talked about before, and we've

00:11:20.133 --> 00:11:24.233
already defined thermocline
and primary productivity.

00:11:24.233 --> 00:11:27.133
I'll be using those terms freely
as we go through the

00:11:27.133 --> 00:11:28.567
discussion today.

00:11:28.567 --> 00:11:33.200
So be sure you're clear on all
of those terminologies.

00:11:33.200 --> 00:11:35.333
So here's a list of some
of the symptoms then.

00:11:35.333 --> 00:11:38.367
So during El Nino you've
got reduced biological

00:11:38.367 --> 00:11:41.667
productivity in the
Eastern Pacific.

00:11:41.667 --> 00:11:44.167
Warm water in the
Eastern Pacific.

00:11:44.167 --> 00:11:45.800
Weak or reversed trade winds.

00:11:45.800 --> 00:11:48.533
Lower pressure in the
Eastern Pacific.

00:11:48.533 --> 00:11:52.767
Rain in the East, and as I'll
show you later on, there are

00:11:52.767 --> 00:11:56.867
some distant climate anomalies
that are connected with El

00:11:56.867 --> 00:12:00.733
Nino, but occur in other parts
of the world as well.

00:12:00.733 --> 00:12:05.333
I'll get to that later
in the lecture.

00:12:05.333 --> 00:12:08.167
So here's kind of
where it began.

00:12:08.167 --> 00:12:10.367
As you saw from the chlorophyll
map, it's a very

00:12:10.367 --> 00:12:15.133
highly productive region along
the Peruvian Coast because of

00:12:15.133 --> 00:12:19.700
the cold water being brought up
in the Humboldt current or

00:12:19.700 --> 00:12:25.267
the Peru current, generally
destabilizing that ocean.

00:12:25.267 --> 00:12:30.033
And then the winds, the trade
winds, with the Ekman layer

00:12:30.033 --> 00:12:34.267
pumping water offshore causing
coastal upwelling bringing

00:12:34.267 --> 00:12:36.900
nutrient rich waters
to the surface.

00:12:36.900 --> 00:12:40.300
Well given that then, and
here's an example of a

00:12:40.300 --> 00:12:44.433
Peruvian fishing boat
catching anchovies.

00:12:44.433 --> 00:12:46.867
Given that understanding, what
would cause such a phenomenon

00:12:46.867 --> 00:12:51.033
where the anchovy catch
increased from the '50s up to

00:12:51.033 --> 00:12:54.400
the '60s, and then in the early
'70s, especially in

00:12:54.400 --> 00:12:56.300
1973, it crashed.

00:12:56.300 --> 00:12:58.967
Well this is a buildup
of the fishing fleet.

00:12:58.967 --> 00:13:06.833
More and more--more and more
fish, and people, and ships

00:13:06.833 --> 00:13:08.400
involved in fishing.

00:13:08.400 --> 00:13:10.133
What would cause
a sudden drop?

00:13:10.133 --> 00:13:11.133
Two possibilities.

00:13:11.133 --> 00:13:13.733
It could be overfishing.

00:13:13.733 --> 00:13:18.133
But it turns out later on
this rebounds again.

00:13:18.133 --> 00:13:19.800
So it turns out it's
not overfishing.

00:13:19.800 --> 00:13:23.100
It was some change in the
natural condition of the

00:13:23.100 --> 00:13:26.733
Eastern Tropical Pacific, and
that was the onset of one of

00:13:26.733 --> 00:13:29.167
the strongest El Nino
situations.

00:13:29.167 --> 00:13:33.033
So it was first defined as
this drop in biological

00:13:33.033 --> 00:13:36.767
productivity, which we know
has something to do with

00:13:36.767 --> 00:13:40.833
coastal upwelling, the stability
of the ocean

00:13:40.833 --> 00:13:45.467
thermocline, and we'll follow
that train of cause and

00:13:45.467 --> 00:13:48.300
effect as we go.

00:13:48.300 --> 00:13:51.367
Here's the way it's
defined today.

00:13:51.367 --> 00:13:54.067
Largely in terms of the surface
temperature of the

00:13:54.067 --> 00:13:57.900
Pacific Ocean, and the depth
of the thermocline.

00:13:57.900 --> 00:14:04.533
So during La Nina, you have
generally a steeply inclined

00:14:04.533 --> 00:14:10.500
thermocline, deeper in the
Western Pacific with lots of

00:14:10.500 --> 00:14:12.133
warm water then.

00:14:12.133 --> 00:14:15.600
But shallower in the Eastern
Pacific, which means the cold

00:14:15.600 --> 00:14:17.700
water is brought up
very close to the

00:14:17.700 --> 00:14:21.600
surface, even to the surface.

00:14:21.600 --> 00:14:24.133
The normal condition is halfway
in between, and then

00:14:24.133 --> 00:14:28.367
the El Nino situation is when
the thermocline is flatter

00:14:28.367 --> 00:14:29.733
across the Pacific Ocean.

00:14:32.267 --> 00:14:35.667
Remember the Date Line is in
here, so this is 120 East and

00:14:35.667 --> 00:14:38.533
this is 80 degrees West.
The Date Line is

00:14:38.533 --> 00:14:40.667
somewhere in there.

00:14:40.667 --> 00:14:43.900
But this means you've got a big
deep layer of warm water

00:14:43.900 --> 00:14:45.167
near the Eastern--

00:14:47.600 --> 00:14:51.600
in the Eastern part of the
Tropical Pacific preventing

00:14:51.600 --> 00:14:55.600
efficient mixing of nutrient
rich waters to the surface.

00:14:55.600 --> 00:15:00.133
So that's the way we envision
this today after 30 or 40

00:15:00.133 --> 00:15:02.500
years of study.

00:15:02.500 --> 00:15:06.500
And the Walker circulation looks
something like this.

00:15:06.500 --> 00:15:11.333
Now, in the normal circulation
you get strong trade winds,

00:15:11.333 --> 00:15:15.633
rising motion over the warm
pool, and then a return of air

00:15:15.633 --> 00:15:18.333
aloft towards the East
and then sinking.

00:15:18.333 --> 00:15:21.800
During the Walker circulation
that is weaker and breaks up

00:15:21.800 --> 00:15:25.333
and you get rising motion in
the East. And this may

00:15:25.333 --> 00:15:26.067
exaggerate it.

00:15:26.067 --> 00:15:29.833
This shows an actual reverse
trade winds.

00:15:29.833 --> 00:15:31.133
That isn't always the case.

00:15:31.133 --> 00:15:35.533
But at least they are weaker
than they would be during the

00:15:35.533 --> 00:15:36.933
typical situation.

