00:18:54.867 --> 00:18:59.867
One of the ways we monitor El
Nino is to keep track of the

00:18:59.867 --> 00:19:05.567
ocean surface temperatures in
these four kind of commonly

00:19:05.567 --> 00:19:06.700
defined areas.

00:19:06.700 --> 00:19:12.767
All the scientists who work on
El Nino agree to monitor these

00:19:12.767 --> 00:19:13.967
four temperatures.

00:19:13.967 --> 00:19:15.867
Sea surface temperature
in area one,

00:19:15.867 --> 00:19:17.467
two, three, and four.

00:19:17.467 --> 00:19:21.167
So you'll find plot, for
example, of Nino four or Nino

00:19:21.167 --> 00:19:24.833
three, a temperature plotted
as a function of time.

00:19:24.833 --> 00:19:26.333
It's right on the Equator.

00:19:26.333 --> 00:19:30.133
Usually it goes 5 degrees North
to 5 degrees South, and

00:19:30.133 --> 00:19:32.733
that's kind of a commonly
agreed upon way

00:19:32.733 --> 00:19:35.400
to monitor El Nino.

00:19:35.400 --> 00:19:36.500
And here's how it's done.

00:19:36.500 --> 00:19:43.000
So there's a rather remarkable
array of buoys that was put in

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:47.833
a decade or so ago across the
Equator in the Pacific.

00:19:47.833 --> 00:19:51.600
Many of these have thermistor
chains that go down into the

00:19:51.600 --> 00:19:55.300
ocean a couple hundred meters,
so you can monitor not only

00:19:55.300 --> 00:19:57.633
conditions at the surface,
but subsurface

00:19:57.633 --> 00:19:59.400
temperatures as well.

00:19:59.400 --> 00:20:02.033
That's where that diagram
about the depth of the

00:20:02.033 --> 00:20:08.067
thermocline came from, looking
at the thermistor chain data

00:20:08.067 --> 00:20:10.900
dangling beneath these buoys.

00:20:10.900 --> 00:20:13.600
But you can log in, you can just
go to their website at

00:20:13.600 --> 00:20:17.567
anytime day or night and get
current data for what the

00:20:17.567 --> 00:20:19.833
ocean is doing in this
part of the world.

00:20:19.833 --> 00:20:22.133
So it makes it a very if you've
got a new theory, if

00:20:22.133 --> 00:20:25.100
you've got a better theory than
anyone else, you can test

00:20:25.100 --> 00:20:28.067
it immediately because this data
is available, not only

00:20:28.067 --> 00:20:31.867
historically going back 10
years or so, but it's

00:20:31.867 --> 00:20:35.200
available day by day, so you
can test new theories and

00:20:35.200 --> 00:20:37.467
maybe make predictions.

00:20:37.467 --> 00:20:41.200
So it's become a very kind of
open-ended egalitarian subject

00:20:41.200 --> 00:20:44.100
where anybody with a better
idea can put it forward

00:20:44.100 --> 00:20:48.600
because the data is there
for anybody to work on.

00:20:52.300 --> 00:20:55.767
So here's a couple
of plots then.

00:20:55.767 --> 00:21:00.333
One is the ocean temperature
departures for the combination

00:21:00.333 --> 00:21:04.000
