00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:07.467
And then below that is the SOI,
the Southern Oscillation

00:21:07.467 --> 00:21:10.667
Index, which is defined as the
pressure difference, it's

00:21:10.667 --> 00:21:13.633
Tahiti minus Darwin.

00:21:13.633 --> 00:21:17.067
Right, Tahiti is the
Eastward-most station of the

00:21:17.067 --> 00:21:21.767
two, and Darwin is, of course,
is in Northern Australia.

00:21:21.767 --> 00:21:24.367
So be sure you get the
sign of this right.

00:21:29.133 --> 00:21:31.800
So, you know, you wouldn't
expect to find such a tight

00:21:31.800 --> 00:21:36.267
relationship between these two
rather different quantities.

00:21:36.267 --> 00:21:38.200
One is a sea surface
temperature, one is an

00:21:38.200 --> 00:21:40.200
atmospheric pressure.

00:21:40.200 --> 00:21:42.267
However there is a relationship
between the two,

00:21:42.267 --> 00:21:44.200
and I think let's see
which way it works.

00:21:44.200 --> 00:21:51.900
So when the Eastern Tropical
Pacific is warmer, that means

00:21:51.900 --> 00:21:56.267
Tahiti has a let's see, which
way does that work.

00:21:56.267 --> 00:22:02.733
By the way, this is plotted not
in pressure units, but in

00:22:02.733 --> 00:22:06.333
units of standard deviations.

00:22:06.333 --> 00:22:08.700
So there's a normal fluctuation
to this pressure

00:22:08.700 --> 00:22:10.200
difference.

00:22:10.200 --> 00:22:13.000
You compute the standard
deviation and then you mark

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:16.633
whether you are close to
normal relative to one

00:22:16.633 --> 00:22:20.500
standard deviation, or one
or two or three standard

00:22:20.500 --> 00:22:22.767
deviations away from normal.

00:22:22.767 --> 00:22:24.767
So that's the way that is.

00:22:24.767 --> 00:22:26.833
That standard deviation, again,
I think is the quantity

00:22:26.833 --> 00:22:30.833
you're dealing with
in lab this week.

00:22:30.833 --> 00:22:38.967
So generally, when you have
warmer conditions you have

00:22:38.967 --> 00:22:44.467
lower pressure in Tahiti
relative to Darwin.

00:22:44.467 --> 00:22:48.433
That would make sense because
if there's warmer conditions

00:22:48.433 --> 00:22:57.167
in the East, which would be this
condition, with warmer

00:22:57.167 --> 00:23:01.000
air aloft hydrostatically,
that would mean lower

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:03.000
atmospheric pressure
beneath it.

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:05.300
So there is a physical law
connecting these two, but

00:23:05.300 --> 00:23:08.533
still, it's a bit interesting
that it comes out to be such a

00:23:08.533 --> 00:23:09.700
nice relationship.

00:23:09.700 --> 00:23:13.467
