00:40:14.267 --> 00:40:16.800
So it's a little odd because
we're jumping from El Nino,

00:40:16.800 --> 00:40:21.000
which is primarily a Tropical
phenomenon, to the study of

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:23.900
ice in the climate system,
which is primarily a high

00:40:23.900 --> 00:40:25.333
latitude subject.

00:40:25.333 --> 00:40:28.300
But they're both very important
in the way the

00:40:28.300 --> 00:40:32.100
atmosphere and the ocean work
to form our climate.

00:40:32.100 --> 00:40:36.933
I wanted to first just run
through a set of definitions

00:40:36.933 --> 00:40:40.967
for the different types of ice
that we'll be interested in.

00:40:40.967 --> 00:40:47.433
Sea ice is frozen seawater,
where you take seawater, you

00:40:47.433 --> 00:40:51.900
blow cold wind over it, you draw
the heat out of it, you

00:40:51.900 --> 00:40:54.133
bring it down to the freezing
point, and then

00:40:54.133 --> 00:40:55.667
eventually you freeze it.

00:40:55.667 --> 00:40:58.700
That is sea ice.

00:40:58.700 --> 00:41:03.933
Ice sheets, like Greenland and
Antarctica, are large plateaus

00:41:03.933 --> 00:41:08.600
of ice formed from
compacted snow.

00:41:08.600 --> 00:41:11.800
Snow that fell month after
month, year after year, piled

00:41:11.800 --> 00:41:14.700
up, squeezed, compressed
to form ice.

00:41:14.700 --> 00:41:16.867
So the origins of these
two things are

00:41:16.867 --> 00:41:18.067
almost completely different.

00:41:18.067 --> 00:41:21.533
In one case you freeze seawater,
the other case you

00:41:21.533 --> 00:41:24.133
just compact snow.

00:41:24.133 --> 00:41:30.433
Glaciers are streams
of moving ice.

00:41:30.433 --> 00:41:32.533
They're moving under the
influence of gravity.

00:41:32.533 --> 00:41:36.633
So normally if you've got a
snow fall on the top of a

00:41:36.633 --> 00:41:40.533
mountain that builds up, after
a while it gets deep enough,

00:41:40.533 --> 00:41:43.700
it begins to be pulled
gravitational down the slopes

00:41:43.700 --> 00:41:46.033
of the mountain.

00:41:46.033 --> 00:41:52.233
Ice shelves are fixed,
floating ice sheets.

00:41:52.233 --> 00:41:56.367
They're basically ice that's
come off an ice sheet, flowed

00:41:56.367 --> 00:41:59.233
down to sea level in a glacier,
and then has spread

00:41:59.233 --> 00:42:05.767
out over the ocean surface
still fixed to the land.

00:42:05.767 --> 00:42:08.767
I'll show you diagrams
of all of these.

00:42:08.767 --> 00:42:10.600
Icebergs, I'm sure you
know that one.

00:42:10.600 --> 00:42:16.133
Those are chunks of drifting,
floating ice broken off from

00:42:16.133 --> 00:42:18.100
glaciers or ice shelves.

00:42:18.100 --> 00:42:20.333
And then, of course, on land,
you can have permanent or

00:42:20.333 --> 00:42:23.367
seasonal snow fields, just
areas that have received

00:42:23.367 --> 00:42:26.267
either just snow for that winter
and it's going to melt

00:42:26.267 --> 00:42:30.300
off the next summer, or snow
that is able to persist over

00:42:30.300 --> 00:42:33.933
the summer season and still be
there the next year would be

00:42:33.933 --> 00:42:36.833
called a permanent snow field.

00:42:39.600 --> 00:42:44.300
So these are important terms
in the descriptions I'll be

00:42:44.300 --> 00:42:48.267
going through mostly
next time.

00:42:48.267 --> 00:42:49.467
These are equally important.

00:42:49.467 --> 00:42:53.567
These are the physical
properties of ice that we'll

00:42:53.567 --> 00:42:57.533
need to know in order to
understand the way ice works

00:42:57.533 --> 00:42:59.367
in the climate system.

00:42:59.367 --> 00:43:03.400
First of all, there's
this latent heat

00:43:03.400 --> 00:43:07.633
of melting or freezing.

00:43:07.633 --> 00:43:09.467
You can look it up,
you can Google it.

00:43:09.467 --> 00:43:15.300
The value is 334,000 Joules
per kilogram.

00:43:15.300 --> 00:43:20.500
Every time you take water and
freeze it, you have to remove

00:43:20.500 --> 00:43:22.967
that much heat.

00:43:22.967 --> 00:43:27.233
And every time you take ice and
melt it, you have to put

00:43:27.233 --> 00:43:30.233
that same amount of
heat back in.

00:43:30.233 --> 00:43:32.300
So it's a reversible process.

00:43:32.300 --> 00:43:36.767
That number applies to either
melting or freezing.

00:43:39.300 --> 00:43:40.833
And you can do that in
a variety of ways.

00:43:40.833 --> 00:43:44.167
You can radiate that heat away,
you can have cold winds

00:43:44.167 --> 00:43:47.800
or warm winds, provide that
heat, or remove that heat.

00:43:47.800 --> 00:43:50.200
But in any case, whenever you're
melting or creating

00:43:50.200 --> 00:43:53.667
ice, you've got to deal with
that amount of heat.

00:43:53.667 --> 00:43:54.767
It's a large number.

00:43:54.767 --> 00:43:58.533
It's not as large as the latent
heat of condensation.

00:43:58.533 --> 00:44:01.033
Remember, the latent heat of
condensation was many times

00:44:01.033 --> 00:44:02.767
that number.

00:44:02.767 --> 00:44:05.833
You might want to look back and
see what that number was.

00:44:05.833 --> 00:44:09.167
This is still big, but it's not
as big as a number needed

00:44:09.167 --> 00:44:14.067
to condense water or
to evaporate water.

00:44:14.067 --> 00:44:16.833
I want to remind you also that
while the freezing point of

00:44:16.833 --> 00:44:21.400
fresh water is zero degrees
Celsius in fact, that's the

00:44:21.400 --> 00:44:27.100
basis on which the Celsius
scale is defined for salt

00:44:27.100 --> 00:44:30.400
water with a salinity of
approximately 35 parts per

00:44:30.400 --> 00:44:34.800
thousand, that freezing point
is depressed to about minus

00:44:34.800 --> 00:44:36.600
two Celsius.

00:44:36.600 --> 00:44:40.733
You'd have to cool the water a
bit colder if it's sea water

00:44:40.733 --> 00:44:41.967
before it'll start to freeze.

00:44:45.400 --> 00:44:48.233
This third bullet, I'm sure you
know this, but I want to

00:44:48.233 --> 00:44:51.967
impress on you how
remarkable it is.

00:44:51.967 --> 00:44:56.967
Most objects, most materials,
when you freeze them from the

00:44:56.967 --> 00:45:01.867
liquid they reduce
their volume.

00:45:01.867 --> 00:45:04.933
That is, they become
more dense.

00:45:04.933 --> 00:45:08.533
Almost every subject known
to man does that.

00:45:08.533 --> 00:45:11.333
Water is one of the very few
exceptions that when you

00:45:11.333 --> 00:45:14.733
freeze it it actually expands.

00:45:14.733 --> 00:45:16.633
I think the only other
one that I know that

00:45:16.633 --> 00:45:19.700
does this is bismuth.

00:45:19.700 --> 00:45:24.067
Bismuth has that same property
of water as when you condense

00:45:24.067 --> 00:45:27.500
it from the liquid to the solid
it actually expands.

00:45:27.500 --> 00:45:33.067
Now you know this, because if
you leave a bottle of water

00:45:33.067 --> 00:45:36.667
out on a cold night and it
freezes, it'll expand and

00:45:36.667 --> 00:45:38.000
break the jar.

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:39.267
So you know it's expanding.

00:45:39.267 --> 00:45:43.000
You also know it because when
you drop an ice cube into a

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:45.733
glass of water, it doesn't sink
to the bottom, it floats

00:45:45.733 --> 00:45:46.467
on the top.

00:45:46.467 --> 00:45:48.700
You're so accustomed to seeing
that, but I want you to kind

00:45:48.700 --> 00:45:51.800
of marvel at that the next
time you see it.

00:45:51.800 --> 00:45:56.867
That the solid is actually less
dense then the liquid.

00:45:56.867 --> 00:45:59.767
It's a very rare circumstance,
it's a very rare situation.

00:45:59.767 --> 00:46:03.533
But it's very controlling in
the way ice works in the

00:46:03.533 --> 00:46:04.233
climate system.

00:46:04.233 --> 00:46:07.533
The fact that it floats on top
of the ocean, for example,

00:46:07.533 --> 00:46:09.133
rather than sinking
to the bottom.

00:46:09.133 --> 00:46:11.100
It changes everything in
terms of the way the

00:46:11.100 --> 00:46:13.800
climate system works.

00:46:13.800 --> 00:46:19.567
So a typical density for ice
is about 917 kilograms per

00:46:19.567 --> 00:46:22.300
cubic meter.

00:46:22.300 --> 00:46:25.700
Typical density for fresh
water is about 1,000.

00:46:25.700 --> 00:46:29.433
Typical density for sea
water's about 1,025.

00:46:29.433 --> 00:46:34.067
So this is less dense than both
of those, and would float

00:46:34.067 --> 00:46:38.933
either in fresh water
or in seawater.

00:46:38.933 --> 00:46:40.167
Any questions on that?

00:46:42.500 --> 00:46:43.467
This is an interesting one.

00:46:43.467 --> 00:46:48.233
If you've got a bucket of
seawater and you freeze it, or

00:46:48.233 --> 00:46:54.367
start to freeze it, as the water
freezes, it'll expel

00:46:54.367 --> 00:46:56.967
most of the salt.

00:46:56.967 --> 00:47:00.900
So that if you take a chunk of
that ice that you formed and

00:47:00.900 --> 00:47:05.367
melt it, the salinity is going
to be far less than the salt

00:47:05.367 --> 00:47:06.467
water it was made from.

00:47:06.467 --> 00:47:07.633
I'll give you an example.

00:47:07.633 --> 00:47:10.133
If you start with a bucket of
ocean water with a salinity of

00:47:10.133 --> 00:47:16.000
say, 35 parts per thousand, and
you froze it very slowly,

00:47:16.000 --> 00:47:19.100
you could actually generate
ice that when melted had a

00:47:19.100 --> 00:47:22.933
salinity of perhaps only
5 parts per thousand.

00:47:22.933 --> 00:47:25.533
It really does expel most
of the salt when

00:47:25.533 --> 00:47:28.333
you freeze that water.

00:47:28.333 --> 00:47:31.567
And that plays a big role, as
you might imagine, in the way

00:47:31.567 --> 00:47:33.067
the Arctic Ocean works.

00:47:33.067 --> 00:47:39.133
When you form sea ice, the water
beneath it gets saltier

00:47:39.133 --> 00:47:44.467
because you've expelled that
salt into the ocean.

00:47:44.467 --> 00:47:46.833
The Inuit people know this.

00:47:46.833 --> 00:47:55.000
When they're out travelling over
the sea ice hunting, if

00:47:55.000 --> 00:47:58.367
they need water, well, you could
dig a hole through the

00:47:58.367 --> 00:48:02.633
ice and get sea water to drink,
but humans cannot live

00:48:02.633 --> 00:48:04.933
on seawater, it's too salty.

00:48:04.933 --> 00:48:07.800
But they could knock
off a chunk of--

00:48:07.800 --> 00:48:09.800
of course, the best thing would
be if there's snow.

00:48:09.800 --> 00:48:12.033
If there's snow on top
of the ice, gather

00:48:12.033 --> 00:48:12.967
that up and melt it.

00:48:12.967 --> 00:48:14.833
That'll be fresh water.

00:48:14.833 --> 00:48:18.600
But if there's no snow on the
ice, take a chunk of the sea

00:48:18.600 --> 00:48:22.000
ice and melt it down and
you could live on that.

00:48:22.000 --> 00:48:24.533
It's not very tasty, it's
brackish water, but you could

00:48:24.533 --> 00:48:29.233
live on that because it's enough
fresher than the ocean

00:48:29.233 --> 00:48:33.767
water was, that the human can
exist on that particular kind

00:48:33.767 --> 00:48:35.200
of brackish water.

00:48:35.200 --> 00:48:37.233
So this is important.

00:48:37.233 --> 00:48:41.400
For climate purposes it's
important that ice and snow is

00:48:41.400 --> 00:48:45.367
highly reflective of sunlight.

00:48:45.367 --> 00:48:50.200
The typical albedo for
ocean water is

00:48:50.200 --> 00:48:53.333
something less than 0.1.

00:48:53.333 --> 00:48:58.067
It absorbs more than 90% of
the light that hits it.

00:48:58.067 --> 00:49:04.700
On land, a more typical albedo
is something like .2, 0.2.

00:49:04.700 --> 00:49:08.233
But yet for ice and snow, the
albedo is more like 0.8.

00:49:08.233 --> 00:49:12.100
In other words, something like
80% of the radiation that hits

00:49:12.100 --> 00:49:14.233
it is reflected back to space.

00:49:14.233 --> 00:49:16.933
And that, as you can imagine,
albedos playing such an

00:49:16.933 --> 00:49:19.667
important role in climate,
that's an important role for

00:49:19.667 --> 00:49:24.000
ice controlling the albedo
of the surface.

00:49:24.000 --> 00:49:26.600
And the last one I want to
mention is that ice, while we

00:49:26.600 --> 00:49:29.933
think of it as something
brittle, when you take a chunk

00:49:29.933 --> 00:49:33.200
of ice and hit it with a hammer,
it will shatter.

00:49:33.200 --> 00:49:36.233
When it's under high enough
pressure it'll flow like a

00:49:36.233 --> 00:49:38.600
liquid, like a viscous liquid.

00:49:38.600 --> 00:49:41.400
And we'll talk about that when
it comes to how glaciers and

00:49:41.400 --> 00:49:42.333
ice sheets move.

00:49:42.333 --> 00:49:46.033
So review these and we'll start
on the description of

00:49:46.033 --> 00:49:48.400
ice and the climate
system next time.

